      "correct": "This behavior pattern is characteristic of secure attachment (~65% of infants). Securely attached children use their caregiver as a secure base for exploration, show appropriate distress during separation, and are easily comforted upon reunion.",
      "incorrect": {
        "Insecure-Avoidant": "Avoidant children show little distress when the caregiver leaves and tend to avoid or ignore them upon return, unlike the child in this scenario who shows distress and seeks comfort.",
        "Insecure-Resistant (Ambivalent)": "Resistant children cling to the caregiver with little exploration, show high distress during separation, and importantly, both seek AND resist comfort upon return—showing ambivalence. This child was easily comforted, not resistant.",
        "Disorganized": "Disorganized attachment involves contradictory or confused behaviors (e.g., approaching while looking away). This child shows consistent, organized behavior patterns typical of secure attachment."
      }
    }
  },
